e against bureaucrats who do not respect the age-old values of Thai/Siamese social and cultural order. Such values include compassion for the poor and an understanding of urban space as deeply embedded in social and ritual relations. In a gripping account of their standoff, Herzfeld—who simultaneously argues for the importance of activism in scholarship—traces the agile political tactics and styles of the community’s leadership, using their struggle to illuminate the larger difficulties, tensions, and unresolved debates that continue to roil Thai society to this day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCity dwellersxCivil rightszThailandzBangkok. 0aCity planningzThailandzBangkok. 0aEvictionzThailandzBangkok. 0aHistoric districtszThailandzBangkok. 0aUrban beautificationzThailandzBangkok. 0aUrban renewalzThailandzBangkokxCitizen participation. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acultural anthropology, thailand, bangkok, southeast asia, buddhist history, religion, buddhism, buddha, squatters, city government, urban development, pom mahakan, community, political will, politics, legal battles, public relations, policymaking, bureaucrats, culture, age-old values, compassion for the poor, poverty, ritual, activism, activist scholar, citizen participation, grassroots movement, beautification, renewal.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226331751423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226331751/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles